data: # Lesson 20: Control a motor from web

## 1 Overview

In this lesson you will learn how to control the speed and steering of a motor from a browser. This lesson combines the lesson Motor Control and lesson Setting up a web server using Bottlepy.

## 3 Connections

Below, you can find the schematic:
Below, you can find a visual representation of the connections:

## 4 Code

The code is based on the lesson Motor Control, but this time we will modify
the speed of the motor using a slider and the direction using two buttons from a
browser.

At the beginning of the code we will import the necessary modules
from the bottle library and the **Rpi.GPIO** library as **GPIO**. Next, we will set
the GPIO in **BOARD** mode, declare the pins used by the motor driver and set
them as **OUTPUT**. For the pin used to modify the speed we will create a
PWM instance and initialize this instance with a duty cycle of **0**. We need a
variable that will store the speed in the course of the code. The initial value of
this variable will be 100, meaning that the motor will run at 100% speed.

Next, we have to deal with the routes for our user interface. For that, we need
a route to the default location, which is /. For this route we have created a function
that uses **template** to send the **index.html** page to the default location.

We need four more routes. One that will receive from the web interface the
state of the slider, which is also the speed of the motor. This function is similar with
the ones for the sliders from the previous lesson. The only difference is that we need
to indicate that the new state of the slider needs to modify the global **motorspeed**
variable.

Another route is attached to the forward button. For this we have a new
function, **forward()**, function created to turn on the motor forward. We have three
main instructions: the first one is for setting the speed of the motor, the second one is
for setting the **DIRA** pin to **LOW** and the last one is setting the **DIRB** pin to **HIGH**.

The **backward()** function turns on the motor backwards, and it is similar
with the **forward()** function, the only difference is that we need to set the **DIRA** pin
to **HIGH** and the **DIRB** pin to **LOW** (this will change the direction).

We also need another route which has associated a function that will stop the
motor. This function is **stopp()** and here we need to set the speed pin to **LOW**. In this
case, the direction pins are irrelevant, but we can set them to LOW.

The code will end with a run call that will listen to HTTP requests on all
interfaces. This run is located inside a **try-except** block so that when we will
interrupt the connection, we can clean the used GPIO ports.

Now, let's discuss about the HTML page. In the **head** of the page we will put
the links for Bootstrap, jQuery and Font Awesome. In the **body** we will create two
buttons using Font Awesome, and when one button is pressed, using JavaScript we
will call a function to rotate the motor. Also, there is a slider that controls the speed
of the motor. When the state of the slider is modified, the new value will be sent to
the server and the **motorspeed** variable will be changed. The HTML page is
structured using Bootstrap grid system, and if you have trouble understanding the
HTML **body**, please check the theory lesson.

In order for the buttons and the slider to work, we had to insert into the page
a script that sends the values for the slider to the server. For the slider we are using
the event **change**, a variable that reads the state of the slider and an ajax call that
will trigger the **setmotorspeed()** function, sending the slider value along with it. For
the buttons we are using two events, so that the page can run flawlessly on devices
with or without touch capabilities. **touchstart** and **mousedown** are used when the
button is pressed and, using **ajax**, we will call a function that will start the motor
forward or backward, depending on which button is pressed. **touchend** and
**mouseup** are used when the button is released and a function will be called to stop
the motor.

"""
*   Credits: www.plusivo.com
*
*   Lesson 20: Control a motor from web
*
*   The code below is created for the lesson "Control a motor from web"
*   where you will host a simple website and modify the speed of the
*   motor from a browser using a slider and the direction using two buttons
*
*   More information about can be found in the guide.
*
"""

#import the necessary modules from the bottle library
from bottle import route, run, template, request
#we will import the RPi.GPIO library with the name of GPIO
import RPi.GPIO as GPIO

#we will set the pin numbering to the GPIO.BOARD numbering
GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BOARD)

#the next variable stores the pin used to control the speed of the motor
motorspeed_pin = 8

#the next two variables store the pins used to control the direction of the motor
DIRA = 10
DIRB = 22

#we will set the pins as output
GPIO.setup(motorspeed_pin, GPIO.OUT)
GPIO.setup(DIRA, GPIO.OUT)
GPIO.setup(DIRB, GPIO.OUT)

#the motorspeed_pin will be used as an enable pin on the motor driver
pwmPIN = GPIO.PWM(motorspeed_pin, 100)

#we start the pwm instance with a duty cycle of 0
pwmPIN.start(0)

#define a variable that will store the speed of the motor
motorspeed = 100

#define the route for the main page
@route('/')
def index():
    #at the '/' route we will return the index.html
    #template that is in the views folder
    return template('index.html')

@route('/setmotorspeed', method = 'POST')
def setmotorspeed():
    #get the speed from the web page
    global motorspeed
    motorspeed = int(request.POST.get('motorspeed'))

    #send a message to the user
    return 'ok'

@route('/forward')
#the forward() is called for moving the motor in one direction
#(let's say forward)
def forward():
    #set the speed of the motor
    pwmPIN.ChangeDutyCycle(motorspeed)

    #set the direction of the motor to forward
    GPIO.output(DIRA, GPIO.LOW)
    GPIO.output(DIRB, GPIO.HIGH)

    #send a message to the user
    return 'ok'

@route('/backward')
def backward():
    #set the speed of the motor
    pwmPIN.ChangeDutyCycle(motorspeed)

    #set the direction of the motor to backward
    GPIO.output(DIRA, GPIO.HIGH)
    GPIO.output(DIRB, GPIO.LOW)

    #send a message to the user
    return 'ok'

@route('/stopp')
#define a function to stop the motor
def stopp():
    #this instruction is used to set the speed of the motor to 0 (Off)
    pwmPIN.ChangeDutyCycle(0)

    #in these instructions the state is irrelevant because the speed is 0
    GPIO.output(DIRA, GPIO.LOW)
    GPIO.output(DIRB, GPIO.LOW)

    #send a message to the user
    return 'ok'

try:
    #we will run the app on port 5000
    run(host = '0.0.0.0', port = '5000')

except KeyboardInterrupt:
    pass

#clean the used ports
GPIO.cleanup()
